title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link
type="local"
href="ring-0001.xml"
addr="ring-0001"
title="Ring">Ring</fr:link>s. We define their <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Product Ring</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}\times  R_{2}]]></fr:tex> to consist of the direct product of the underlying set of elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex>, equipped with the operations
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(a,b)+(c,d)=(a+c,b+d)]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(a,b)(c,d)=(ac,bd).]]></fr:tex>
This forms a ring.</fr:p><fr:p>Moreover, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> are both commutative, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}\times  R_{2}]]></fr:tex> is commutative.</fr:p><fr:p>And if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{2}]]></fr:tex> are both unital, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R_{1}\times  R_{2}]]></fr:tex> is unital.</fr:p>
 
   
